Buffalo Bore is introducing a truly Heavy 30-30 Winchester loading. This new load utilizes a 190gr. custom Hawk bullet and gives the venerable 30-30 here-to-for unrealized power and is designed so that the person who owns a 30-30 can now reliably kill elk or moose sized game. The 30-30 can now be carried as a defensive tool in grizzly country and will be much more effective in stopping a grizzly attack than any other 30-30 ammunition in the world. This heavy 30-30 load is not designed for deer, although it will kill deer and if you line them up right, it will kill three or four deer with one shot……….

The custom 190gr. hawk bullet is designed with a harder core and thicker than normal jacket, so the expansion is minimal, thus insuring very deep penetration which is needed to break large bones and destroy organs deep inside large game animals. This load generates an unreal 2100 fps from normal 20 inch carbines—this is the type of velocity that the ordinary 170gr. 30-30 loads generate, but again, we are using a 190gr. bullet. The product SKU# for this load is 28A/20

2020 fps -- Win. Model 94AE 16 inch Trapper carbine circa 1992
1983 fps -- Savage 99 26 inch rifle circa 1917 - Not a Typo
Note that the longest barrel gave the slowest velocity and even the short 16 inch Winchester trapper model gives faster speeds than the 26 inch Savage 99 rifle, which shows that barrel length is not always the sole indicator of velocities a firearm will generate.
Buffalo Bore always uses stock over-the-counter- firearms that give real world velocities. Other ammunition companies normally use laboratory test barrels which give much higher velocities than stock firearms. We at Buffalo Bore see this long established practice as misleading to the consumer.

This 30-30 loading (Item 28A/20) is safe to use in ANY/ALL 30-30 chambered firearms that are in normal operating condition—no exceptions, no need to “double check” with us.

The Rock Island Armory 1911 series consists of a product line of single-action recoil operated semi-automatic pistols. They are designed and manufactured by Armscor in Marikina City, Philippines, and distributed in the United States by Armscor USA, located in Pahrump, Nevada.

RIA (Rock Island Armory) 1911s are clones of the US Military G.I. M1911-A1, the standard issue US Service pistol from 1911 to 1985. Most RIA models are targeted for the low-end price point of the 1911 pistol market and are basic entry level MIL-SPEC versions of the 1911, however, the RIA Tactical, Compact, and Match models offer additional semi-custom high end features. The Compact model features a skeletonized hammer and beavertail grip safety while the Tactical model also adds a target-grade hammer and trigger as well as an ambidextrous safety, and enhanced contrast combat sights. Armscor is an ISO 9001 certified-compliant company which manufactures Rock Island pistols using CNC (Computer Numerical Control) equipment. RIA 1911 series pistols are constructed of 4140 chromoly steel with a cast frame, and are available in .45 ACP, .38 Super, 9mm Luger, and .22 TCM chamberings.

title: For Sale:  Imez Makarov IJ70-17A, .380 ACP LNIB, 2 magazines
postcontent:
Want to thumb your nose at the gun ban crowd? Now's your chance to do it in style with a high quality example of solid Russian engineering, all steel and built to last!

This was my first carry sidearm in the 90s but I need to streamline my collection, so I present this fine gun for your consideration. If there's any question, I am the original purchaser of the pistol in 1995, so you can be assured it's been well cared for and never abused or mistreated.

You'll be getting a proven, dependable pistol in this one. I confess I was a bit concerned by its small ejection port when I first purchased it, but I've put a variety of .380s through this Makarov, from inexpensive FMJ range ammo through fancy defensive hollowpoints like Cor-Bon and Remington Golden Saber and I can tell you it's been totally reliable.

No surprise that the pistol's interior is typical Russian: rough as a cob...but everything works beautifully. Adjustable sights and a decocking safety are nice additions that make this gun a pleasure to shoot, as you'll find. The chromed barrel's easy to clean and spotless with no problems, as is its feed ramp.

The IJ70-17A comes complete with its original factory box, spare 8 round magazine, manual and tools. About the only visible clue that the pistol saw use is that being left-handed, I cut off the lanyard loop, smoothed the stubs and blued them for protection and aesthetics. If you're a stickler for absolute authenticity, you can find original black grips with the loop, Russian made and marked as this is with 'Baikal' on eBay all day long.

Please be prepared to present your TN driver's license or handgun carry permit to assure me you're legally able to purchase this firearm, and be willing to sign a bill of sale.

I have no ability to ship this, local FTF only.

title: For Sale:  H&K P7M8 Squeezecock 9mm
postcontent: Heckler & Koch unveiled this pistol design in 1976, marketing is as the perfect auto-loading police-use pistol. The reason it is considered ideal is due to its completely unique safety system, namely the "squeezecocker" control surface built into the front of the grip. When the operator picks up the firearm, the main shooting hand instinctually squeezes the panel rearward, and this action cocks the striker rearward while unlocking the sear for use. The panel is spring-loaded, which means when pressure is reduced, it snaps forward, decocking the striker and locking the trigger. This system is also designed to release the slide when it is locked rearward. This design eliminates the need for a decocker, external safety lever OR slide stop lever, making the sides of the firearm completely flush and reducing overall width. The barrel is fixed (does not cant upwards) which means despite the firearm's compact size, it is capable of printing groups of 2 inches or less at 25 yards. This accuracy is easily comparable to many high-end automatic pistols in production. According to H&K the M8 version is rated for +P ammunition. It has classic three white-dot sights dovetailed into the slide, and comes with one 8 round capacity magazine. I purchased it as "slightly used" and have fired approximately 150 rounds through it without a single jam.

title: For Sale:  Sporterized Mosin Nagant M91/30 with 168x Rounds of Ammo + Extras
postcontent:
This rifle was a project of mine that fell by the wayside when I got into a new hobby (motorcycles). The concept was to build a rifle that shoots very cheap ammo with modern ergonomics. So even though the base cost of building the rifle was similar to the price of a brand new .308 or 30-06, the cheaper 7.62x54r bullets would save me more money over the long term. This is what I accomplished before I lost interest in the project.

- ATI Stock with cheek riser - for a better cheek weld when aiming with scope
- Removed Iron Sights (A lot harder than you think!)
- NC Star Long Eye Relief 2-7x Scope (in order to clear the straight bolt handle)
- Aluminum pillar bedded 
- Barrel cut down to 24 inches and re-crowned at Oregon Timberwolf Custom Gunsmith
- Threaded barrel for Muzzle Brake

To complete the project the rifle would ideally need a bent bolt handle and receiver mount for a scope. Add a nice scope on it and you have an accurate shooting rifle with modern ergonomics that shoots ammo at the fraction of the price of a .308 or 30-06.

The base rifle is a Mosin Nagant M91/30. It was produced from the Izhevsk Arsenal in 1939. It has a round receiver and is a common rifle so it does not have much worth as a collectible (so no, I do not feel bad ruining a piece of history!), but it does have value as a functional rifle with modern ergonomics that shoots better than its original configuration.

The rifle comes with everything you see in the pictures:

- Ultimate Arms Gear Muzzle Brake
- NC Star Long Eye Relief Scope 2-7x Zoom - Illuminated Sights
- 98x Rounds of Bulgarian Surplus Ammo - Silver Tip 147 grn FMJ
- 35x Rounds of Wolf Performance Ammos - Steel Cased 174 grn FMJ
- 35x Rounds of PPU - Brass 182 grn FMJ (The best ammo I've tested so far)
- 15x Steel Stripper Clips - for quick reloading
- 30 inch cleaning rod
- Firing Pin Gauge / Disassembly Tool
- Okie Head Space Gauge (Not Pictured)

I don't have the original wood stock or accessories other than the firing pin tool. You could probably buy that from someone else for cheap if you are feeling nostalgic for 1941.

If you don't like the price then make me an offer, I just might take it!
